		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    A Dark Elves Guide to being a Wizard</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:jasmineeq@yahoo.com">Jasmine</a> | 
		            11/12/1999 4:26:25 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">A Dark Elves Guide to being a Wizard<BR>
By Jasmine Moonflower, Wizard and Spurned of Neriak<BR>
(Bristlebane Server)<BR>
<BR>
*Guide- verb 1: to act as a guide to: direct in a way or course<BR>
2: to direct, supervise, or influence usually to a particular end <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
~ Before you read anything on this guide, it is important that you read the Everquest Handbook (comes in the box with the game) so that you understand all of the EQ terminology and get no misunderstood words from this guide. ~<BR>
<BR>
    I would like to share my experiences with all of the young soloing Dark Elf Wizards out there.  In this guide you will find an efficient way to move smoothly through the younger half of your life with as little hassle as possible.  What I have written within these pages works; it works because as sad as it may sound, I&#8217;m doing it for the third time now.  I&#8217;m a wizard fanatic&#8230; what can I say.  As a wizard fanatic, I respect my fellow wizards views and opinions and even though I know that what I have written here works, I also know there are other ways to get the job done.  I would be a necromancer&#8230; I mean, ignorant to say there wasn&#8217;t.  It has taken me several years of research (ok, maybe just a few months) to complete this guide.  I can only hope that you enjoy it and that it helps you to come to your full potential as a Master Blaster (and no, not the one from &#8216;Mad Max- beyond Thunder Dome&#8217;).<BR>
<BR>
    (Here are a few SUGGESTIONS for character creation.  Choose agnostic for religion unless your personal role playing preferences would prefer otherwise.  The reason is, the wizard relies on the arcane, which has no direct connection to any god.   If you commit to a god, you commit yourself to certain factions that will make future getting around in the world much harder then it will already be.  (The inferior races are quite jealous of our superior abilities as Dark Elves.  This has resulted in many ATTEMPTS to bring our people into extinction.) Intelligence is the most important statistic for a wizard.  Intelligence equals mana and mana is what keeps you alive as a wizard when it really comes down to it.  You can&#8217;t touch a fighter&#8217;s skills when it comes to melee at the higher levels, and don&#8217;t kid yourself... cause you can&#8217;t.  We actually think things out unlike our not so intellectual drooling warrior counterparts.  If you can&#8217;t handle thinking and dealing with the complexities of the arcane, then join the saliva pool and be gone from my sight (as my mentor so colorfully put it).  Anyhow, I&#8217;m not saying put every point into intelligence&#8230;just put as many as you can while still feeling personally comfortable with your other statistics.  My intelligence was 132 when I was done.  =)<BR>
<BR>
In the beginning there was only darkness, our lovely home&#8230; Neriak<BR>
<BR>
    The character is born and &#8216;You are in our world now!&#8217; as Everquest so colorfully puts it!  First things first, find the wizard&#8217;s guild.  Wander around until you have found the Tower of the Spurned located in Commons part of Neriak (Commons is where you should start by default as a wizard).  Turn in the note that is in your inventory to the specified wizard guild leader on the bottom floor of the tower.  In exchange, you will get some experience, faction, and your first robes!  Put those robes on your frail and mostly naked body young wizard!  It&#8217;s the only armor that stands between you and death for now.  Also equip your not-so-trusty rusty dagger (that you already have) into your melee inventory slot.  You also have the option to use your practice points with the guild leader if you choose to do so.  I personally saved mine for later to use on skills that really drive me nuts (-cough- sense heading -cough-) or on a skill I really wanted to learn well or quickly (Research and Magic Specializing).  Practice points is basically the lazy way of getting your skills up instead of actually using the skills.  The only exception is when you learn a skill for the first time, like Meditate, where you will have to put that first practice point in it if you ever want to learn the skill.  You will get 5 practice points every level starting with your first 5 at level one.  Now take a moment to sit down, open your spell book and scribe those 2 spells you have.  Right after that, memorize them into two of the eight icon slots.  As soon as you get up cast the shield spell&#8230;  don&#8217;t wait till you get outside to start practicing those magic skills!<BR>
<BR>
    ((SIDE NOTES about MONEY and STUFF!  You will need money to buy food, water, spells, and future equipment.  When hunting try to only save stackable items at first since you will be limited on room until you can afford to buy a backpack for about 6 gold.  Example of stackable items would be the bone chips of the skeletons, the snake skin&#8217;s of the snakes etc&#8230; in other words, meaning items you can have more then one of in the same inventory slot.  Save any rusty weapons you come upon from those skeletons for they usually fetch a pretty gold or two.  You may have to make a trip or two to Neriak to sell when your inventory fills up&#8230;simply find the nearest merchant in the Foreign Quarters and sell.  (That off melee hand is a nice place to put an extra fire beetle eye to sell or use as an unneeded light source.  After all, why would a superior being such as a Dark Elf need to be hassled with carrying a light source?)  All the merchants should regard you the same in Neriak, so it doesn&#8217;t matter whom you sell to.  A hint on buying a backpack&#8230; there is a luggage equipment dealer in Foreign Quarters of Neriak, find her.  Try to buy equipment from PC tailors or become a tailor yourself!  It is usually much cheaper to make or buy equipment from your fellow players then it is to buy from the stuck up NPC merchants.  My personal recommendation is the recently implemented Silk armors but they can be expensive.  Cloth armor may be the easiest to purchase at first.  ABOVE ALL OF THIS, the most important thing to worry about getting is your spells.  Everything else is a luxury except for the backpack, which will help you gather more stuff, which means more money.  An exact list of your spells can be found on popular web sites such as Everlore or EQ vault.))<BR>
<BR>
And then there was more Darkness, welcome to Nektulos<BR>
<BR>
    After spending the next 3 weeks (well maybe 15-30 minutes tops) fumbling through the dark streets of Neriak, eventually you will find your way through Foreign Quarters and finally out to the lovely and dark forest of Nektulos.<BR>
<BR>
    Nektulos can be trying on anyone&#8217;s patience IF you are careless hunting here; but it&#8217;s definitely the place to hunt for all you can milk it for.  Let me explain... If you are the VERY social type, like lag, waiting on critters to spawn, and possibly dying to wandering NPC&#8217;s (depending on your religion choices)&#8230;  Then you can start your hunting life out in the pale skin infested areas of West Freeport and East Commons (Both located just outside Nektulos) where the humans and imported Dwarves, Halflings, and pale skin Elves tend to hunt.   (A lot of Elves have come to the main continent cause over breeding has made their homelands, Greater Faydwar, overpopulated as they continue to spread like a virus.)  Why go through all of that when you already have a practically Dark Elf exclusive hunting area? (Our wonderful guards do a good job of keeping those pesky low level pale skins &#8216;out&#8217;)  One other thing, your soul is already bound to Nektulos so that if you die, this is where you will be reincarnated with your new body to continue your adventures etc.  (At least until you can change that at later levels or you find someone who is skilled enough to change it for you).<BR>
<BR>
    Few extra words on Nektulos.  This forest is divided into three sections for leveling.  You have a newbies area (level 1 to 4ish) which has the beetles, spiderlings, moss snakes, black wolves, decaying skeletons and a few other critters in it. (Not to mention the famous Newbie Log!)  Then you have the level 4 to 8ish area that is basically going deeper into Nektulos from Neriak which has shadow wolves, skeletons, large spiders, black bears, tree snakes, and a few others.  Finally, the level 8 to 12ish area which is actually on the other side of a river that splits this zone, which you can cross by using the bridge (cant miss it if u stumble upon and follow the path near Neriak to the river (southwards)).   It has young kodiaks, snakes, occasionally will o wisp, more skeletons, Halflings and a few other critters.  (Note you will loose important factions with the Halfling folk for killing the Halflings here.  If you are going for the agnostic approach, be very careful slaying other PC race&#8217;s NPCs) <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Levels 1 - 4<BR>
<BR>
&#8220;It was an awesome fight&#8230; right up until the point where I died.&#8221; &#8211; Camia (Level 1 wizard hunting in Nektulos)<BR>
<BR>
    Your cool, your buffed up with that shield spell, you have spells memorized, your your&#8230; your pathetic... but hey, everyone has to start somewhere, so what to hunt?  Anything that cons white... at level 1 go after moss snakes, decaying skeletons, and black wolves.   (Note&#8230;  if you happen upon a skeleton with a staff and it&#8217;s a cracked staff, switch your dagger out for that!  It does more damage then that puny dagger and it is my observation that a lot of the nicer magical weapons for wizards are one handed blunt).  Watch out for roaming bears, (normal) skeletons, shadow wolves, and anything else that might be trained into the 'newbie&#8217; area.  Once you hit 2nd level, you can add fire beetles to the list.  (Note:  fire beetles and spiderlings aren&#8217;t aggressive until you attack them but once you attack them their friends, if nearby, will join in on the fight)  Level 3&#8230; add spiderlings that con white and blue to the list and try to only attack these and beetles at this point for the sake of gaining the most xp out of every fight.  Always choose the con whites over the blues.  A blue gave me about an 8th of a bubble of xp where a white would give me as much as 3 quarters of a bubble!  Also&#8230; if you are feeling brave you can fight an occasional con white large spider if you happen upon one.  But be warned they poison and there is no guarantee you will win the fight as con whites get tougher and tougher as you go up in levels.  <BR>
<BR>
    Level 4&#8230;  Time to go back to Neriak and pick up some spells!  Sell off what you have if you haven&#8217;t by now and go get some spells.  As I said in my side note about money&#8230; the spells ARE the most important priority once you have a backpack.  Try to get them all if you can!  There are a few utility spells that can only be bought in the library way back in 3rd gate of Neriak, but all the key spells you need for here and now can be found in the Guild Tower.  For combat, the most important spells to get at this point would be the better attack spell, Shock of Fire, and the Area-of-effect spells, Ice Strike and Numbing Cold.  Area-of-effect spells are good for when those spiderlings or other critters gang up on you.   Also for when you need to hit a lot of critters that are close together, usually all engaged by a partner or someone else so they don&#8217;t all come after you once you hurt them!  One catch about AOE spells though, which you will learn, is that some of them might catch you in the effect if you are too close.  Ice Strike is great for hitting all those critters bunched together as long as they aren&#8217;t near you.  For close combat against multiple opponents, the Column series of spells are nice&#8230; such as your level 1 numbing cold spell. (You will see why I class it as a column spell when you see the effect it creates&#8230; very colorful spell!  =)  Root is a must have, but not right now.  It cost much too much mana when you are this young to even bother with.  Think of it this way, the baddies aren&#8217;t worthy of your root spell yet.  Gate is a very nice luxury to have for it teleports you back to your bind point.  <BR>
<BR>
    Thinking of the future&#8230; here is a mistake a lot of wizards make&#8230;  Once you have See Invisibility, practice practice practice!  This spell belongs to the divination school along with your Invisibility spell which, sadly, you won&#8217;t see until 16th level.  If you wait until you have invisibility at 16th, then you will be in for a world of spell fizzling and it will be much slower to advance the skills then for we learn best when we are young.  This applies to your Alteration based spells as well such as Fade (a nice mini random teleport to help get you out of a sticky situation far enough to run for your life).  Once you hit 12th and get Bind Affinity (another very important spell), you will fizzle away a lot of time and mana if the Alteration skill isn&#8217;t honed to its fullest potential.  One last thing before you go back out to the forest&#8230; learn how to Meditate by using your practice points!  You only need to use one point because once your mana runs low and you sit down, open your spell book, and click on the meditate button&#8230;  that skill will start improving like there&#8217;s no tomorrow!  Meditate has 2 very important uses to a Wizard.  The first is it will allow you to regain mana much faster when you use this skill as I said above.  The second use is it will drastically decrease the time it takes to memorize spells.  For the second use, the Meditate skill will automatically kick in once you put an icon in one of your memorizing slots.  <BR>
<BR>
    Now, get back out in that forest with your spells renewed, and see what you can do! (I always recommend getting a &#8216;feel&#8217; for your new spells by trying them on con greens at first)  You will notice your fire spell should be about twice the damage of your previous frost Direct Damage spell!  But beware of the mana consumption from your new spells as well.  Lets move it on out brave wizard&#8230;  deeper into Nektulos to fight black bears and large spiders.  You can also opt to fight tree snakes but you will need your mana consuming root spell for them cause they have some NASTY poison that will most likely kill you even if you win the fight.  If you are brave, you may stumble upon a (normal) skeleton or two you can fight as well.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Levels 5 - 8<BR>
    <BR>
&#8220;Magic can only be gained by acquiring knowledge&#8230; Knowledge IS power...&#8221; &#8211; words of a famous Arch Mage (A few paces behind him laid the corpse of a dead ice-covered Sand Giant, victim of the famous Ice Comet spell.)<BR>
<BR>
    Level 5 is when I started hunting skeletons left and right.  At this point they con anywhere from blue (most likely win) to yellow (most likely gonna get my butt kicked).  Con them and stick to mostly blues and an occasional white if you are feeling lucky punk (Dirty Harry)!  The combat tactics I have been using are actually pretty simple&#8230;pull them with your best spell, then attack em with your weapon while trying to constantly blast with your spells.  Yes your spells will get interrupted a lot, but you will increase your offense, weapon, and defense skills, which improves what little combat skills you have and will desperately need.  The occasional spell that succeeds will be enough to keep your Evocation and Channeling skills rolling.  6th level I continued to hunt skeletons, which were all conning white or blue at this point.  If you get tired of chasing the skeletons around there are a few camps where the skeletons actually spawn.  One camp is a pyramid in the level 4 to 8 hunting area.  Another is an obelisk over in the level 8 to 12 hunting area (on the other side of the river).  To find where exactly these camps are, the easiest thing to do would be to find a map on one of the EQ web sites.  7th you have a couple of options.  You can either continue to hunt skeletons, which will all con blue now, or you can group with a few dark elves in the area that are around your skill and start slaying young kodiaks.  Another option would be to take your first step into the lands of the pale skins (East Commonlands, more data has been written about this zone below) and hunt orc centurions, lions, Giant spiders, lionesses, or young kodiaks with a group.<BR>
<BR>
    Head back to Neriak after you have achieved 8th level and pick up your better attack spells.  Fire Bolt is the better direct damage spell over Shock of Ice but requires a good line of sight (ie the target must be on equal or lower ground then you or the bolt will most likely hit the ground instead of the target.).  The Bolt series of spells can be cast at creatures farther away and out of range of any of the Shock series of spells.  My recommendation is to buy both of these spells if you can.  Pull with and cast the bolt spell whenever you can and if the combat gets to ugly and you are getting hit too much, then cast the quicker casting and more mana efficient Shock of Ice spell.  Here again, the best way to get use to these spells is to test them on some easy victims at first.  Notice that these spells use A LOT of mana.  The Lesser Shielding spell is an upgrade to your Minor Shielding and should definitely replace Minor Shielding once you can afford it.  Shadow Step is an upgrade from fade and random teleports you a little farther while casting a little quicker.  Column of Frost is a respectable replacement over the Numbing Cold spell.  Here again, mind your mana when casting these higher level mana-eating spells.  There are other spells of course, but for combat you really only need the new Direct Damage and AOE spells for now.<BR>
<BR>
Out of the darkness and into the light&#8230;  East Commonlands<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
    Eastern Commonlands isn&#8217;t exactly as bright as the desert, but it is more light then Nektulos and you can actually see the sky.  If you continue down the same path that gets you to the bridge from Neriak and keep heading southwards, the path will end at the zone entrance to East Commons.  This zone from 8th to 12th is the most efficient zone to gain xp.  ((A few things to beware of IF you chose to worship an EVIL god: There is a good chance that the merchants located within the inns scattered through out this zone will Kill you on sight (KOS).  There are some wandering NPC&#8217;s that will be KOS to you as well.  The only one I have encountered whom is based off the same faction as the merchants is a human name Altunic.  He walks past both orc camps every 10 minutes or so and has slain many-a-necro and evil wizards in my presence.  Keep your eyes open and keep hidden while meditating!))<BR>
<BR>
Level 8 &#8211; 12<BR>
<BR>
&#8220;The quill is mightier then the sword.  After all, its what we use to scribe our spells. &#8220;  - old wizard proverb<BR>
  <BR>
  The preferred creatures to hunt in this zone would be the Orc Centurions at either of the Orc camps in this area.  The reason is they drop reasonable loot, are great xp, and give decent faction (plus with the Commonland/Desert of North Ro merchants, Paladins of North Freeport, and The Halfling Guards of Rivervale and only gives negative faction with the Orcs whom wanna kill you anyhow).   When you first come out of Nektulos, follow the zone wall to your right and you will come upon Orc Camp 1.  If you keep following the wall even farther west past the first camp, you will eventually come upon Camp 2, which is the easier of the two camps.  At level 8 you will need a group to fight at either camp.  The other option is to find a partner or 2 and slay Giant spiders, young kodiaks, Lions, or Lionesses.  All of which roam randomly around the north side of the zone.  There are ruins in the desert part of the zone on the south side, but they aren&#8217;t worth the trouble.  Skeletons, which con green at this point, Con red ghouls, and mummies that tend to give you rabies when they it hit you (a disease that slows down hp recovery and last for a long time).  No matter what you fight, you will find yourself more efficient in a group for these next couple of levels only because you don&#8217;t have the firepower to kill most of the critters out here before they can kill you.  For Levels 9 to 12 you should be hunting pretty much the same things in East Commons gradually hunting Orcs more and more over anything else.  Once you hit 12th the Orc Centurions will be conning blue to green and you should now have enough faction that you will be tolerated maybe even able to sell merchants of the respective factions you gained from slaying all the Orcs!   (At level 12 the merchants in the Commonlands and desert were amiable to me, the Paladins of N Freeport apprehensive, the Halfling Guards Indifferent, and the Orcs hated me just as much as they did they day we first met.) At this point its time to move on, but not before running back to Neriak for your Level 12 spells!  <BR>
<BR>
    The key spells to buy for 12th would be Shock of lightning (oh what a wonderful spell) and Bind affinity (another yummy spell).  Shock of lightning is an awesome DD spell that does around 78 damage at first and you don&#8217;t need Line of sight to use it (like all Shock spells), very nice upgrade from Fire Bolt.   Bind Affinity will allow you to bind yourself anywhere you wish.  Be careful to only bind in safe places or you could put yourself in a treacherous cycle of being slain by a monster you can&#8217;t handle over and over again.  I&#8217;ve heard horror stories of casters who have lost 3 or 4 levels before finally receiving help from making this mistake.  Cancel magic is handy for de-buffing Fire-Elementals or removing the effects of Damage-Over-Time (DOT) spells cast on you or your friends.  Yes there are umm&#8230; other spells, by them when you feel like it.  I kept using Column of Frost from level 8 for my AOE spell only cause for the damage the level 12 ones did, they didn&#8217;t seem worth the mana they sucked from me.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Out of the light and into the fire  `Lavastorm Mountains`<BR>
<BR>
Level 12 &#8211; 16<BR>
<BR>
I hunted solo in Lavastorm; only when bored did I group.  It&#8217;s close to home and tons of xp and money to be found.  You can get there by following the zone wall to your right when you first exit Neriak until it leads to an opening that leads to Lavastorm.  There are really only 2 ideal places to hunt solo due to the rock terrain combined with the deadly aggressive Fire Elementals and Imps that roam randomly all over the zone.  Both are near zones to run to in case you get into trouble.  The first in front of Najena and can be reached by following the zone wall to your right from where you first enter Lavastorm.  You can&#8217;t miss the opening to Najena as it is a giant entrance with 2 large broken doors in the front.   The second hunting spot is along the left wall once you clear the zone tunnel that leads into Lavastorm from Nektulos.   Try to make all your pulls to one of these areas.  Closer to the zones wall the better so you can watch for wandering critters.  Level by Level this is what I blew up SOLO...  Level 12- Fire Drakes and an occasional Fire elemental (con blues only).  Level 13- More Drakes, more Elementals, Fire Imps, and Rock Dervish (all con blues only).  Level 14 to 16- Same thing as 13 only I stopped chasing Drakes.   Every night that I hunted in Lavastorm I made no less then 10 platinum pieces.  My hunting tactics at this point were almost always to root and then blow up the baddie.  Occasionally going melee while casting.  Within a few seconds I know if I can blast the critter before he kills me when at melee.  If I don&#8217;t think I can kill him before he kills me or if I had a bad pull I would zone without hesitation.  Discretion is the better part of Valor as it says in your EQ Handbook.  Get your new spells at 16th.  Invisibility, oh so sweet!  With Bind Affinity and Invisibility, they sky&#8217;s the limit as to where you can hunt now.  The new attack spells are Shock of Flame (mana 75 damage 102) and Lightning Bolt (Like the rest of the bolt series, need line of sight.  mana 85 damage 117), both respectable upgrades.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
From this point on, you are officially old enough that you don&#8217;t need me to grab you by the ear and show you where to go and what to do!  I&#8217;m only going to list recommended areas to hunt with only a few highlights.  Good luck to you young Wizard and if you have gotten this far then you are well on your way to becoming a fine Magi indeed!  Below, I listed by level suggested hunting areas that I went to hunt and enjoyed.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
16th- 17th BIG Fire beetles in North Karana.  Reavers in east Karana (normal during the day undead ones at night).  Aqua goblins in Dagnor&#8217;s Cauldron.  &#8220;Undead Lawn Trash&#8221; (you&#8217;ll know what I mean by this when you get there) in the Estate of Unrest.  The Undead at Lake Rathe.  Orcs and crocodiles in the Oasis &#8230;just a few suggestions.<BR>
<BR>
18th &#8211; 20th  Clan Runnyeye (with a group), Orcs in Highpass, and Orcs and Crocodiles in the Oasis.<BR>
<BR>
Ahhh! =)  Level 20, the beginning  of self teleport spells.  The world is your oyster and anything is possible.   The Nektulos teleport you get at 24th level will make selling loot off to merchants never a problem again for the rest of your life.  Simply bind near where you are hunting, gate back to Nektulos, sell your stuff and buy food/water in Neriak, then gate back to your bind point and continue hunting. <BR>
<BR>
Level 20+ There are still things in the outdoor zones you can hunt such as Craig spiders in East Karana or Griffawns located in most of the Karana&#8217;s.  But as you get older you will find more excitement and adventure in the Dungeons of Norrath.  To name a few&#8230;  The Frogloks of Upper (and much later on) Lower Guk located in Innothule Swamp.  Najena (The dungeon is named after the boss who has a nice set of Flowing Black Robes with your name on it =) located near Lavastorm.  Cazic Thule located in Feerot.  House pulls from the Estate of Unrest in Dagnor&#8217;s Cauldron.  Mistmoore located in Lesser Faydwar (if you don&#8217;t mind betraying your Queen whom you will take faction hits with for hunting here). The dragon infested dungeons of Solusek B and Permafrost (only one dragon in each dungeon and yes, they are VERY nasty and you will need tons of people to help you kill them, but this isn&#8217;t for many many levels).  When you are upon your Arch Mage years the planes of Hate and Fear will open to you &#8230; the list goes on and on with only more to come.  Happy blasting my fellow wizards, may the arcane keep you safe!<BR>
<BR>
&#8220;One Last thing before I leave you to die...&#8221; &#8211; Not-so-famous Necromancer. <BR>
<BR>
FACTION<BR>
<BR>
With all this in mind, now would be a good time to clear up some potential faction problems that slowed me down and how to fix some of them.  Even as an Agnostic, there were still quite a few people who wanted my head on their desk as a scroll weight.  It would be safe to say that for someone who worships the Father of Pain, the faction would only be tougher then what I had to deal with.  Of course from a Role playing point of view the agnostic is stated (during character creation) as someone who will most likely find more luck with the other races in the world then with his own people.  If you follow the path of Hate then you probably get your jollies off on being hated (grin).  Below I have listed only a few of the factions I encountered and fixed and couldn&#8217;t fix in my adventures (keep in mind this is accurate only for you agnostic Dark Elf wizards out there).<BR>
<BR>
Humans of Freeport were not too much of a problem, at least not in East or West FP.  I got the usual glowers and I am working on this by slaying Orcs in Highpass Hold. To get into the paladin guarded N Freeport I had to kill a considerable amount of Deathfist Orcs.  Rivervale was only a problem near the entrance when you first zone in from Kithicor Woods.  The clerics aren&#8217;t too fond of us and glared at me everytime I saw them.  Glares means they will most likely kill me if I get to close.  All I can say here is Invisibility is your friend.  I didn&#8217;t have a problem with any of the other factions in Rivervale (ie they only glowered at me).  I couldn&#8217;t sell anywhere there of course but I was able to get the guards to amiable from all the orcs previously slain combined with slaying some of the Runnyeye goblins in the Misty Thicket (especially the named goblin, Mooto) and Clan Runnyeye.   The Pale skin Elves of Greater Faydwar&#8230; heh, you take a guess.  You can get this faction up (but why?) by slaying Crushbone Orcs and freeing the Elf/Dwarf slaves in Crushbone located near Greater Faydwar, but you will loose faction with the Warriors guild in Neriak (the Indigo Brothers). =(   The Dwarven guards are actually starting to like me due to all the Goblins I was killing in Runnyeye.  I heard rumors that I can raise faction with the Dwarven merchants by slaying Bandits at a camp located somewhere in Butcher Block, still haven&#8217;t tested this though the source I got the info from is reliable.  The Gnomes I&#8217;m not sure about but everyone tells me we are ok with them because they are a neutral race.  The Barbarians love to kill us and that&#8217;s not an easy faction to fix at all.  Highpass Guards and citizens all glowered at me.   I recently have been slaying Orcs in the Pass, which has been slowly raising my faction with the Kithicor Wood&#8217;s residents and Highpass guards.  Once I get up to apprehensive I will be moving on (just gives me merchants to sell to in Kithicor in the event I don&#8217;t wish to teleport back to Nektulos).  The Qeynos area humans and merchants were Glowers mostly, all depending on whom I bumped into.  You can slay gnolls in Black Burrow to raise faction with the Surefall Glade folks (Rangers and Druids near Qeynos), Qeynos Merchants, and the Qeynos guards.  There are TONS of other factions out there and I could write a guide on this alone, but I&#8217;m not going to.  Just be sure to /Consider anyone whom you are not sure about.  As a Dark Elf it is more important to our survival then most others (except trolls and ogres who tend to be hated even more due to their savage tendencies&#8230; &#8220;It&#8217;s a troll!  He&#8217;s gonna eat us, kill him!!!&#8221;)<BR>
<BR>
This concludes my guide and I hope you have enjoyed it as much as I enjoyed writing it.  I&#8217;d like to thank all the animals, monsters, and other bad guys, especially Mooto, who have given their lives to make this guide possible.<BR>
<BR>
~ Flame them all ~<BR>
<BR>
Jasmine  @--))------<BR>
<BR>
(Jasmine Moonflower of the Bristlebane Servor/jasmineeq@yahoo.com)<BR>

